# WPD challenge
## Choosing discharge rate

 Optimal discharge given a known demand $D(t)$ should leave the grid-supplied electricity at or below a threshold $G$, where $\int_{32}^{42} \min(D(t) - G, 0) = C_{d,32}$, or the capactiy of the battery at the beginning of the peak period $\{k \in [32,42]\} $.  Since time is given in discrete intervals, we are solving for $G$ in  
$$  \sum_{k=32}^{42} \min(L_{d,k} - G, 0) = C_{d, 32}$$
![](data:image/png;base64,)
Since we don't know in advance for which $k$  $G< L_{d,k}$,  we can't solve this equation by re-arranging terms.  Instead,  we treat the left-hand side  $\sum_{k=32}^{42} \min(L_{d,k} - G, 0)$ as a piece-wise linear function of $G$, $f(G)$, where each linear piece $f_k$ defined on an interval $[L_{d,k}, L_{d,k+1})$.   Solving this requires solving for each $f_k$ and checking to see which candidate solution for $G$ falls in domain for $f_k$.  Since the function $f$ is increasing, there should be a unique $k$ for which this is true.
